rComments: Oh dear. I can't even begin to explain how utterly vague the assignments are. You know that meme where everyone is arguing between getting 4 or 16 on an exam question, but you got South Africa? Yeah that's pretty much this course.
Absolutely awful lecture organization. Atrocious midterm questions considering the little amount of time given.
teacherRatingTags: ['Tough grader', 'Graded by few things', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: Prof. McCourt was actually the reason why I got into genetics. All of his lectures are about understanding and grasping concepts as supposed to memorization. You just have to attend lectures and understand the main ideas then you will definitely do fine on the assignments and midterm. He is very passionate and genetics and it is actually inspiring.

Great prof that is extremely enthusiastic and dedicated to genetics. His lectures aren't like many of the other profs in the sciences with the lecture slides. He is much more interactive and it is very similar to high school class experience. This class isn't a memorization course but a application course so don't expect to just regurgitate info.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Amazing lectures', 'Graded by few things']

rComments: Are you looking at going into genetics research? Take this course over HMB265. You definitely have to work harder, but the content is much more useful and interesting. Study groups are more helpful in this class than in any other. It takes a lot of work to do very well in his section, but if you can't follow, he will gladly help you through it.

Pros: Enthusiastic,concept-based,little memorization,interactive Cons: Disorganized notes and teaching style,hard tests and assignments,doesn't clarify certain terminologies making it hard to grasp some concepts,tend to upload lecture notes during/after lecture,no structured readings  Fun if interested but take HMB265 if you're not into genetics!

he is the best prof i have come across in university yet.  If you are into genetics you will find his lectures worth every second of your time. a bit unorganized and tests are a hard if you don't understand the concepts in depth. he went over experiments and theories in a way that makes you feel you yourself are conducting the experiments.

He is engaging and interested in what he is teaching. He teaches almost entirely in problemsexamples but it's unstructured and often you don't know the concept that these examples are for. His lectures would make an excellent book but are not at all useful when it comes to  his tests. There are no structured readings. Midterm median was 35%.
Very disorganized
His midterm is so hard that class average is around 50%. Do not take his BIO260! Go take HMB265!

His lectures are engaging. He does not spit out facts, but rather uses a Socratic approach so that the class can critically analyze the concepts being talked about. He helps your critical thinking skills. He is not out to screw you if you have studied hard, but the tests & assignments are a bit hard.

A great teacher who understands that science does not mean being able to regurgitate millions of facts.  His lectures were entertaining and to the points and the test was fair.  However, he can be very condescending, especially when you disagree with him.  He tends to shrug you off with a joke and a wave of the hand.

His lectures are free-flowing, and not disorganized, like some people believe. He encourages participation during the discussions, and students that do participate benefit a lot from it. He knows his stuff. The class was very interesting too.
don't like his lecture style, could be more organized. but overall good prof still.
No Comments
Good lecturer - gives interesting background info on how some genetics problems were solved. Funny. Won't feed you any BS. Difficult assignments but fair tests - your marks should even out!
his style of teaching would have made him a very suitable highschool teacher but is utterly unsuited to university teaching.  I rue the day i forked over $400+ to have HIM as a "professor"
Best peof I've had at U of T.  Teaches to think instead of asking to memorize.  I'm thinking of doing plant genetics in grad school just so I can have him as my advisor.
funally no memorizing monkey work.. this is what real science is about
Although I did horribly on the midterm, I still think that McCourt is one of the best profs in the botany department...

A fine professor who is to be commended as one of the only MGB/BCH/IMM type profs who does not emphasize memoriztion.  No he teaches thought and problem solving and he tests on it.  I would have done better on his tests if I had studied more.
Great lecturer, made the course very enjoyable.
This prof is awesome. He teaches the class like a big seminar, and focusses on understanding, rather than the rote memorisation common to other second year courses.
